    <statement><p>Add or subtract the rational expressions to a single rational expression and then simplify. If applicable, state the restricted domain.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{{\frac{2y}{y+2}+\frac{y}{y-2}-3} =}</m> <fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>-\frac{2\mathopen{}\left(y-6\right)}{\left(y+2\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-2\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
   {\frac{2y}{y+2}+\frac{y}{y-2}-3} 
      \amp = {\frac{2y}{y+2}} \cdot \frac{(y-2)}{(y-2)} + {\frac{y}{y-2}} \cdot \frac{(y+2)}{(y+2)} - \frac{3}{1} \cdot \frac{(y+2)(y-2)}{(y+2)(y-2)} \\
      \amp = \frac{2y(y-2)}{(y+2)(y-2)}  + \frac{y(y+2)}{(y+2)(y-2)} - \frac{3(y+2)(y-2)}{(y+2)(y-2)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{2y(y-2)+y(y+2)-3(y+2)(y-2)}{(y+2)(y-2)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{2y^{2}-4y+y^{2}+2y-3(y^{2}-4)}{(y+2)(y-2)} \\
      \amp =  \frac{2y^{2}-4y+y^{2}+2y-3y^{2}+12}{(y+2)(y-2)} \\
      \amp = {\frac{-2y+12}{\left(y+2\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-2\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Notice that <m>{-\frac{2\mathopen{}\left(y-6\right)}{\left(y+2\right)\mathopen{}\left(y-2\right)}, \left(-\infty ,\infty \right)}</m> is also correct. We should actually factor whenever possible, in case we can reduce the rational expression.</p>
</solution>
